Prepare the data¶

In [0]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

used_columns = ['Pclass', 'Sex', 'Age', 'SibSp', 'Parch', 'Fare', 'Embarked', 'Survived']
X_columns = ['Pclass', 'Age', 'SibSp', 'Parch', 'Fare', 'Sex_male', 'Embarked_C', 'Embarked_Q', 'Embarked_S']
Y_columns = ['Survived']

def load_data(fn):
    return pd.read_csv(fn).set_index('PassengerId')

def to_array(data):
    return pd.get_dummies(data).astype(dtype='float32')

def data_preprocessing():
    global train, test
    train = load_data('./train.csv')
    test = load_data('./gender_submission.csv').join(load_data('./test.csv'))  

    train['is_train'] = True
    test['is_train'] = False
    data = pd.concat([train, test])

    # Replace missing values with mean
    data.fillna(data.mean(), inplace=True)

    # Split test and train
    train, test = data[data['is_train']], data[data['is_train'] == False]

    # No unused columns
    train, test = train[used_columns], test[used_columns]

    train, test = to_array(train), to_array(test)
data_preprocessing()


def split_to_x_y(data):
    return to_array(data[X_columns]), to_array(data[Y_columns])

def get_data():
    return split_to_x_y(train), split_to_x_y(test)

def unlabel_data(*sets):
    return ((part.values for part in subset) for subset in sets)

Create an explainer function using LIME¶

In [0]:
def explain(x, explainer=explainer, model=model):
    # LIME
    lime = explainer.explain_instance(x.values[0], model.predict_proba)
    lime.show_in_notebook(show_table=True)

6.¶

Comment on the results for points (4) and (5)

  1. LIME decompositions for different observations comparision

    The model consistently considers the sex of a person as a main disadvantage and surprisingly - the value of the sex (whether the person is a male of a female) does not matter so much - it still is the biggest negative. The situation is similar with the fare - it may vary from 0 up to 82, but for all the observations it has a positive impact. Fortunately the importance of the fare and the sex varies among the observations so the model takes it in the consideration differently. It might be caused by the fact, that model did not normalize the impact of the variables and it might be an interesting point for the future investigations. The importance of class, fare and age differ among the selected observations although those are the three most important variables, exept the observation with hight number of siblings (just after the sex). As already mentioned - the high number of siblings (8) impacts the result much more then the usual 0 and 1 values. Finally we have the city of Embarkation and the most impactful one - Southampton, which is considered as a negative in contrast to Cherbourg.

  2. Differences between two models

    Two compared models behave very differently on the selected observation. While the first one is able to correctly predict, that the person died, the second one makes a mistake and thanks to the explanation we can spot the meaningful differences. Both models treat the sex of the person as a main disadvantage (key negative factor) and fare (which is quite low compared to 35.6 mean value) as the main positive factor, the second model neglects the negative impact of the age, and surprisingly - the class. This causes it to predict differently than the first model and might be a field to improve this model. There is another visible difference - one of the models treat the number of parents / children aboard the Titanic (which in this case is 0) as a positive while the other as a negative. It is not the most important factor, but if the situation occurs with more variables, it might be the reason of the discrepancy.
